Exploratory Data Analysis¶

One striking difference between 3xTG and healthy neurons is that the 3xTG neurons seem to be more excitable - lower threshold for spiking, lower step current required to cause spiking. Another is that the spike width appears to be larger in 3xTG cells than in healthy cells.¶

This is supported by the fact that when $\theta_m$ (Vmo) and $\sigma_m$ (dVm) are plotted against each other, we find a reasonably well defined boundary between the sets of estimated values for each neuron type. Whenever $\theta_m$ increases in a given family of estimates, $\sigma_m$ also increases to compensate, keeping the overall excitability of the neuron relatively constant.

We find, using variable importance in random forests, that the half-width of a neuron and the voltage at half inactivation ($\theta_h$) for the sodium current are key distinguishing features between 3xTG healthy neurons. Our decision tree uses width as the first feature to split on. Models with larger estimated widths are much more likely to be classified as 3xTG.

The results of the plot of $\theta_m$ against $\sigma_m$ suggests that an important feature distinguishing neurons of the two classes from each other is overall excitability. Therefore an engineered feature containing this information is desirable. Two features in particular have this property. One is the maximum applied step current which will not cause the neuron to generate an action potential. The other is the voltage at which this occurs.

The separation between the two classes of neurons is especially striking when the half-width and the threshold step current are plotted against each other. This is reflected in the decision tree structure, where these features are consecutive, informative splits.

We would likely see even better splits if we included $\theta_h$ in a third dimension, as it is the third consecutive split in our decision tree structure, and it is also fairly informative as measured by the gini information. A gini value close to 0.5 corresponds to a good split, and these values are about 0.5, 0.3, and 0.2, respectively.

We see plots of threshold voltage or minimal threshold current against $\theta_h$ both have the same pattern and seem to split 3xTG and healthy neurons from each other well.

The rate of change of $I_{Na}$ is a good proxy for $\theta_m$. Because $I_{Na}$ activates very quickly and inactivates relatively more slowly, we expect that the rate of change of $I_{Na}$ with respect to time during an action potential will be maximum when we are the steepest part of the sigmoid, which is $\theta_m$. If we plot these two quantities against each other, we find that this is indeed the case. The correspondence is not exact since the rate of change of $I_Na$ also depends on voltage and $h$ is changing, but we will nevertheless use the voltage at maximum $\dot{I}_{Na}$ as a proxy for $\theta_m$.

We also expect to see some separation when we look at the threshold voltage for generating a spike, and we expect this threshold voltage to be correlated with the voltage at which $I_{Na}$ turns on. We do see that the separation is not perfect, as the differences between the two kinds of neurons is multifaceted and includes spike width, which is a proxy for parameters like $\sigma_{ht}$, $t_h$, $g_K$, and $\theta_n$, which also differ between the two classes of neurons. There are also other interactions of parameters which mostly account for these differences. As the differences between the two classes of neurons is rather subtle, these interactions may become more complicated as one wishes to decrease the error rate, but one need not traverse the decision tree too deeply to find good separation between the two classes.

# Scale and visualize the embedding vectors
digits = datasets.load_digits(n_class=6)
def plot_embedding(X, title=None):
    
    x_min, x_max = np.min(X, 0), np.max(X, 0)
    X = (X - x_min) / (x_max - x_min)

    plt.figure()
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    colors = ['blue', 'red']
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        plt.text(X[i, 0], X[i, 1], str(Y_train.values[i]),
                 color=colors[Y[i]],
                 fontdict={'weight': 'bold', 'size': 9})

    if hasattr(offsetbox, 'AnnotationBbox'):
        # only print thumbnails with matplotlib > 1.0
        shown_images = np.array([[1., 1.]])  # just something big
        for i in range(X_train.shape[0]):
            dist = np.sum((X[i] - shown_images) ** 2, 1)
            if np.min(dist) < 4e-3:
                # don't show points that are too close
                continue
            shown_images = np.r_[shown_images, [X[i]]]
            
            
            
            imagebox = offsetbox.AnnotationBbox(
                offsetbox.OffsetImage(digits.images[len(Y_train.values[i])], cmap=plt.cm.gray_r),
                X[i])
            ax.add_artist(imagebox)
    plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)

Constructing Neuron Identity from Predictors¶

We assign our predictors and labels divide the data into training and test sets. At first we are interested in seeing whether we can use information from the predictors to tell us what the neuron identity of each epoch label is. We will do this by looking for the errors in our classification algorithm. The tool to look at these errors is the confusion matrix, which we will visualize below.

In [36]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize = (20,20))
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    #else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    #print(cm)

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('confusion_matrix.png')

Random Forests¶

I tested a number of machine learning algorithms and found that random forests had the best performance in assigning neuron labels given the data set I examined. Random forests uses an average of decision trees trained from random samples of the training data. This classification algorithm is good at detecting nonlinear interactions between parameters, which is nice because that means we don't have to do as much feature engineering to do classification well. The disadvantage is that it is a bit of a black box and it is hard to tell why the algorithm worked and what the differences are between the different categories. Since HH models are nonlinear and it can be difficult to interpret what the differences are between sets of estimated parameters, it is not clear whether one could design simple features which would help distinguish different neurons from each other.

Determining Features Distinguishing 3xTG and Healthy Neurons¶

Next, we can train a random forests algorithm to determine which features are the most important in distinguishing healthy and 3xTG neurons from each other. We drop a number of features that are not useful in distinguishing these classes since the difference in features reflect superficial differences in the stimulating currents eliciting the recorded data.

def split_train_test(neuron_params, label_vars, drop = []):
    trains = [neuron_params[neuron_params['epoch label'] == neuron].sample(frac=0.9) for neuron in all_neurons]
    tests = [neuron_params[neuron_params['epoch label'] == all_neurons[i]].loc[~neuron_params[neuron_params['epoch label'] == all_neurons[i]].index.isin(trains[i].index)] for i in range(len(all_neurons))]
    train = pd.concat(trains)
    test = pd.concat(tests)
    
    if isinstance(label_vars, (str)):
        label_vars = [label_vars]
    
    drop1 = [x for x in list(train) if (('Na' in x) and ('Min' in x) and ('dot' not in x)) or (('K' in x) and ('I' in x) and ('Max' in x) and ('dot' not in x))]
    drop2 = [x for x in list(train) if ('$g$' in x or '$g_' in x) and ('Min' in x)]
    #drop3 = [x for x in list(train) if ('freq' in x)]
    drop3 = ['Mean Response AHP to Step (mV)', 'Max Response AHP to Step (mV)']
    drop4 = [feature_dict[label_var] for label_var in label_vars] + [feature_dict['epoch_label'], feature_dict['Neuron'], feature_dict['Type'], 'Min m']
    drop5 = [x for x in list(train) if ('dot{I}$' in x) or ('$I$' in x)]
    drop6 = [x for x in neuron_params if 'infty' in x]
    drop7 = ['Max m', 'Max h', 'Max n', 'Min m', 'Min h', 'Min n', 'Min $\dot{g}_{K}$ Upstroke (nS/ms)']
    drop8 = [x for x in neuron_params if '$g$' in x]
    drop9 = [x for x in neuron_params if 'dot{g}$' in x]
    drop10 = ['Voltage at Max $\dot{I}_{K}$ Upstroke (mV)', 
             'Voltage at Min $\dot{g}_{Na}$ Downstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Max $g_{Na}$ Downstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Max $\dot{g}_{K}$ Upstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Min $\dot{I}_{K}$ Downstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Min $\dot{I}_{K}$ Upstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Min $\dot{g}_{Na}$ Upstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Min $I_{K}$ Upstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Max $\dot{g}_{Na}$ Downstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Max $\dot{g}_{K}$ Downstroke (mV)',
             'Voltage at Min $\dot{g}_{K}$ Upstroke (mV)']
    
    drop_set = drop + drop1 + drop2 + drop3 + drop4 + drop5 + drop6 + drop7 + drop8 + drop9 + drop10
    
    X_train = train.drop(drop_set, axis = 1)
    Y_train = train[[feature_dict[label_var] for label_var in label_vars]]
    X_test = test.drop(drop_set, axis = 1)
    Y_test = test[[feature_dict[label_var] for label_var in label_vars]]
    
    return X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test

We can print out the features which are most useful in distinguishing the types from each other. Here we list the first 20. Some of the features which stand out are the half-width, $\theta_h$ (the voltage at half inactivation of the sodium current), the resting membrane conductance, the threshold voltage, and the maximum step current which does not elicit a spike. Only two of these features are parameters in the model. Further down the list, $\sigma_{ht}$ and $t_{h0}$, constants associated with the relaxation time of the inactivation of sodium, make an appearance before the other parameters in the model. We show later that when each of these parameters in a 3xTG neuron is tuned into the region of parameter space corresponding to healthy neurons, other key 3xTG features are transformed into healthy values.

min_g_inc, min_g_dec, and $g_L$ are all very similar, as they are slightly different representations of the resting membrane conductance. min_g_inc is the minimum total conductance when the voltage waveform is increasing with time.

Decision Tree¶

We can get a little more insight into how the two types of neurons are different by looking at a decision tree. Fortunately, the decision tree is pretty accurate overall. When looking at the leafs of the decision tree, we see that we do not have to go into very much depth in the tree to make good classifications. Thus, it is fairly straightforward to differentiate 3xTG and healthy cells from each other. The colors of the nodes distinguish which category of cell is the majority class. The direction down the tree, left or right, corresponds to True or False. From the decision tree, 3xTG cells tend to have a larger spike width, a larger resting conductance, and a sodium current which tends to inactivate at lower voltages. Overall, 3xTG are more excitable, requiring a smaller minimum step current to initiate spiking, which tends to occur at lower voltages. From the decision tree, we can see that $\sigma_{ht}$ and $t_h$ are also important in distinguishing healthy and 3xTG neurons from each other. We will discuss why this might be below.

I wasn't able to get the decision tree embedded in the notebook. It can be generated as a pdf file with the command given in the comments for the code below

Next, we are interested in determining whether or not we can use our model to show how to go from a neuron with 3xTG features to a neuron with healthy features. This could mean increasing the threshold voltage of the neuron, decreasing the spike width, and increasing the minimal step current necessary to produce a spike. Since we know that $\theta_m$, $\sigma_m$, $\theta_h$, $\sigma_{ht}$, and $t_{h}$ are involved somehow, we should first see what happens when we change these quantities. Of course, other parameters which alter the mechanisms responsible for spike generation are fair game too. However, we choose these quantities as these are some of the most important ones picked out by data assimilation as being the parameters which may be underlying the differences in features.

class MultiOutputRF(object):
    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        self.args = args
        self.kwargs = kwargs
        
    def fit(self, X, Y):
        X, Y = map(np.atleast_2d, (X, Y))
        assert X.shape[0] == Y.shape[0]
        Ny = Y.shape[1]
        
        self.clfs = []
        for i in range(Ny):
            clf = RandomForestRegressor(*self.args, **self.kwargs)
            Xi = np.hstack([X, Y[:, :i]])
            yi = Y[:, i]
            self.clfs.append(clf.fit(Xi, yi))
            
        return self
        
    def predict(self, X):
        Y = np.empty([X.shape[0], len(self.clfs)])
        for i, clf in enumerate(self.clfs):
            Y[:, i] = clf.predict(np.hstack([X, Y[:, :i]]))
        return Y

def correlate(feature, features_train, labels_train):
    
    features_train[feature_dict[feature]] = labels_train
    
    corrs = features_train.corr()

    corrs_feature = corrs[feature_dict[feature]].sort_values(ascending = False)
    
    return corrs_feature.iloc[1:]

    if isinstance(features, (str)):  
        
        random_forest = train_regr_forest(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    
        correlations = correlate(features, X_train.copy(), Y_train.copy())
    
        var_imp1 = pd.Series(random_forest.feature_importances_, index = list(X_train))
    
        print(var_imp1.index.get_duplicates())
    
        var_imp1 =  pd.concat([var_imp1, correlations], axis = 1)
    
        var_imp1.columns = ['Var Imp', 'Correlation']
    
        var_imp1 = sorted(zip(list(var_imp1.index), list(var_imp1['Var Imp']), list(var_imp1['Correlation'])), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)[0:20]
    
    else:
        
        extra_trees = train_regr_extra(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
        
        var_imp1 = sorted(zip(list(X_train), list(extra_trees.feature_importances_)), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)[0:20]
    
    print('full', var_imp1, '\n')
    
    tree_clf = train_regr_tree(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    make_regr_tree_fig(tree_clf, X_train, features, handle = 'full')
    
    #X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test = split_train_test(neuron_params, feature, drop = drop + [])
    
    #random_forest = train_regr_forest(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    
        
    #tree_clf = train_regr_tree(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    #make_regr_tree_fig(tree_clf, X_train, feature, handle = 'full_all')
    
    #X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test = split_train_test(neuron_params, feature, drop = drop + list(neuron_params)[21:])#+
                                                   #[feature_dict['Cm'], feature_dict['gL']])
        
    #random_forest = train_regr_forest(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    
    #var_imp3 = sorted(zip(X_train, random_forest.feature_importances_), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)[0:20]
    #print('params_all', var_imp3, '\n')
    
    #tree_clf = train_regr_tree(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    #make_regr_tree_fig(tree_clf, X_train, feature, handle = 'params_all')
        
    X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test = split_train_test(neuron_params, features, drop = drop + list(neuron_params)[21:]+
                                                   [feature_dict['Cm'], feature_dict['gL']])
    
    if isinstance(features, (str)):
        
        random_forest = train_regr_forest(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    
        correlations = correlate(features, X_train.copy(), Y_train.copy())
    
        var_imp4 = pd.Series(random_forest.feature_importances_, index = list(X_train))
    
        var_imp4 =  pd.concat([var_imp4, correlations], axis = 1)
    
        var_imp4.columns = ['Var Imp', 'Correlation']
    
        var_imp4 = sorted(zip(list(var_imp4.index), list(var_imp4['Var Imp']), list(var_imp4['Correlation'])), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)[0:20]
    
        feature = features
    else:
        
        extra_trees = train_regr_extra(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
        
        var_imp4 = sorted(zip(list(X_train), list(extra_trees.feature_importances_)), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)[0:20]
        
        feature = '_'.join(features)
        
    print('params', var_imp4, '\n')
    
    tree_clf = train_regr_tree(X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test)
    make_regr_tree_fig(tree_clf, X_train, features, handle = 'params')
    
    header1 = ['Features Predicting {0}'.format(handle), 'Var Imp', 'Correlation']
    header2 = ['All Params Predicting {0}'.format(handle), 'Var Imp', 'Correlation']
    
    #var_imps1 = [w + x  for w,x in zip(var_imp1,var_imp2)]
    #var_imps2 = [w + x for w,x in zip(var_imp3,var_imp4)]
    
    save_var_imp(var_imp1, '{0}_Feature'.format(feature), header1)
    save_var_imp(var_imp4, '{0}_Params'.format(feature), header2)

def dV_dt(V, m, h, n, params, I):

    return 1.0/params['Cm']*(params['gNa']*m**3*h*(55.0 - V) + params['gK']*n**4*(-90.0 - V) + params['gL']*(params['EL'] - V) + I)
    
def sigmoid(V, theta, sigma):
    return 0.5*(1 + np.tanh((V - theta)/sigma))

def tau(V, t0, t1, theta, sigma):
    
    return t0 + t1*(1 - np.tanh((V - theta)/sigma)**2)
    
def dm_dt(V, m, params):

    return (sigmoid(V, params['Vmo'], params['dVm']) - m)/tau(V, params['t0m'], params['t1m'], params['Vmo'], params['dtVm'])

def dh_dt(V, h, params):    
    return (sigmoid(V, params['Vho'], params['dVh']) - h)/tau(V, params['t0h'], params['t1h'], params['Vho'], params['dtVh'])

def dn_dt(V, n, params):
    return (sigmoid(V, params['Vno'], params['dVn']) - n)/tau(V, params['t0n'], params['t1n'], params['Vno'], params['dtVn'])

def NaKL(x,t,I,params):
    
    [V, m, h, n] = x
        
    dV_dt_ = dV_dt(V, m, h, n, params, I)
    dm_dt_ = dm_dt(V, m, params)
    dh_dt_ = dh_dt(V, h, params)
    dn_dt_ = dn_dt(V, n, params)
    
    return dV_dt_, dm_dt_, dh_dt_, dn_dt_

    dt = 0.4
    det = qs.detector(5.0, 30)
    times = det.send(V)
    
    f_times = qs.filter_times(times, 50, len(V) - 50)
    spikes = qs.peaks(V, f_times, 10, 18)
    
    upsample = 3
    
    times, aligned = qs.realign_spikes(f_times, spikes, upsample=upsample, jitter=4)
    
    width = 10000
    
    average_aligned = np.mean(aligned, axis = 0)
    
    time = np.linspace(0.0, (dt*len(average_aligned) - dt)/upsample, len(average_aligned))
    
    spline = UnivariateSpline(time, average_aligned-(max(average_aligned) + min(average_aligned))/2, s=0)
    r1, r2 = spline.roots() # find the roots

    print(new_width)

def ensure_dir(f):
    d = os.path.dirname(f)
    if not os.path.exists(d):
        os.makedirs(d)

def plot_data(directory, path, time, estimate, prediction, data, current):
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (15,10))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(211)

    ax.plot(time, data, color = 'black', linewidth = 5, label = 'Data')
    ax.plot(time[:len(estimate)], estimate, color = 'blue', label = 'Estimate')
    ax.plot(time[len(estimate):], prediction, color = 'red', label = 'Prediction')
    ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
    
    ax.set_ylabel('voltage (mV)', size=20)
    
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(212)
    
    ax2.plot(time, current, color = 'purple', label = 'Current')
    ax2.set_xlabel('time (ms)', size=20)
    ax2.set_ylabel('current (pA)', size=20)
    ax2.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
    
    plotfile = '{0}/path_{1}/est_pred{1}.png'.format(directory, path)
    ensure_dir(plotfile)
    fig.savefig(plotfile, bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.close()
    
def save_data(directory, path, time, estimate, prediction, data, current):
    
    estimate = np.vstack((time[:len(estimate)], estimate)).transpose()
    prediction = np.vstack((time[len(estimate):], prediction)).transpose()
    data = np.vstack((time, data)).transpose()
    current = np.vstack((time, current)).transpose()
    
    
    estimate_file = '{0}/path_{1}/estimate{1}.dat'.format(directory, path)
    prediction_file = '{0}/path_{1}/prediction{1}.dat'.format(directory, path)
    data_file = '{0}/path_{1}/data{1}.dat'.format(directory, path)
    current_file = '{0}/path_{1}/current{1}.dat'.format(directory, path)
    
    ensure_dir(estimate_file)
    
    np.savetxt(estimate_file, estimate, fmt = '%.8g')
    np.savetxt(prediction_file, prediction, fmt = '%.8g')
    np.savetxt(data_file, data, fmt = '%.8g')
    np.savetxt(current_file, current, fmt = '%.8g')

def load_data(neuron, path):
    
    dir = 'Neuron{0}'.format(neuron)
    specs_file = '{0}/{1}'.format(dir, 'specs.txt')
    
    specs_file = open(specs_file).readlines()
    
    problem_length = 2*int(specs_file[0].strip()) + 1
    skip = int(specs_file[1].strip())
    dt = float(specs_file[2].strip())/2
    
    estimate = np.loadtxt('{0}/data{1}.dat'.format(dir, path))
    predict = np.loadtxt('{0}/predict{1}.dat'.format(dir, path))
    time = np.linspace(skip*dt, (skip + problem_length + len(predict[:,0]))*dt-dt, problem_length + len(predict[:,0]))
    
    data = np.loadtxt('{0}/Vs_noisy_2kHz.dat'.format(dir))[skip:len(time) + skip]
    current = np.loadtxt('{0}/current_2kHz.dat'.format(dir))[skip:len(time) + skip]
    
    voltage_estimate = estimate[:,1]
    voltage_prediction = predict[:,0]
    
    param_file = '{0}/path_{2}/params{2}.dat'.format(dir, neuron, path)
    
    print(param_file)
    
    params = np.loadtxt(param_file, dtype=bytes)
    
    params = dict(zip(params[:,0].astype(str), params[:,-1].astype(float)))
    
    return params, estimate, data, current

def get_data(label_to_neuron, epoch, path):
    
    data = ['data', 'current', 'estimate', 'predict', 'params']
    
    for datum in data:
    
        f = 'boom:CA1_Neurons/Protocol_1f/{0}/{1}{2}.dat'.format(epoch, datum, path)
        g = 'Neuron{0}/{1}{2}.dat'.format(label_to_neuron[epoch], datum, path)
        ensure_dir(g)
        
        subprocess.call('scp {0} {1}'.format(f, g), shell = True)

Finally, we are interested in seeing whether we can decrease the excitability and spike-width of a 3xTG cell. We will integrate our estimated model of a 3xTG neuron forward in time using a step current as a stimulus. We find that if we increase $\theta_h$ by 10 (from -46 mV) and $\theta_m$ (from -20 mV) by 5 simultaneously (but not independently), we can increase the minimum required step current to produce a spike from about 70 pA to about 270 pA and increase the threshold voltage from about -50 mV to -40 mV. This has no effect on the spike width, however. This can be seen in the first plot below.

Next, in addition to the previous modifications, we can also decrease $\sigma_{ht}$ by 20 mV (from about -3 mV) and decrease $t_{h0}$ by a factor of four. This decreases the spike width from about 2.76 ms to about 2 ms. It does lower the minimum required step current to initiate a spike by about 70 pA (to 200 pA), but note that this is still well within the healthy range for this parameter, according to data assimilation and our decision tree.

Decreasing $\sigma_{ht}$ to more negative values widens range at which the inactivation variable $h$ for the sodium current changes slowly. This enables us to decrease the value of $t_{h0}$ overall, which at more positive voltages causes the sodium current to inactivate more quickly, shortening the width of the spike. The net effect on the shape of $t_h$ is to increase its value near voltages important for spike generation so that we don't preempt spikes altogether by decreasing $t_{h0}$, but to otherwise increase the rate of inactivation during an action potential. Without changing the value of $\sigma_{ht}$, we cannot decrease the value of $t_{h0}$ by much.
